^B@2^*Bhondo717:^*N|cp||at| I had several questions about how opener makes a forcing bid. As I think many of you know, new suits by responder are always forcing. So, as long as responder keeps bidding a new suit, opener cannot pass.  The reason for that is, typically, responder is "captain" of the hand and more often than not, responder decides the final contract. Therefore, responder needs a way to keep the bidding open to determine what the best contract is. However, the same is not true of opener. A new suit by opener is not forcing.|
PG| ***** 90 ***** |


nt||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717:^*N|cp||at| So, if you have 18+ points as opener, and partner has responded to your opening bid, opener knows that their side must be in game. Since partner is showing six, and you have 18, you have enough for game, more or less. Therefore, you must make a jump bid to show your points. Over 1@S, lisa has to jump to show her 19 points, and establish a game force. Her two choices are 3@D and 2N. Technically, she does not have the distribution for 2N, but since she has two Ax doubletons, I think 2N is a very reasonable choice. 3@D is her other choice.|
