^C@2nome: As added emphasis on Howard's teaching I have decided each week to collect many of his important @E@3instructions in one page under "Howard's Pearls"  which we can go over them many times. The following are my picks. I am sure you can find many more.

|FP|2|cp|8|at|
^C@2** |FP||cp||at|When partner opens 1@D and you have both 5+ clubs and a 4 card major. If you have a game forcing hand, you bid 2@C first and then your major; that sequence establishes a game force. If you have less than a game forcing hand you bid your major and ignore your clubs, because you do not have enough points to force to game by bidding 2@C and then your major
|FP|2|cp|8|at|
** |FP||cp||at|In general, leading away from tenaces can be dangerous, particularly in a suit contract. So you should avoid them on opening lead in particular against suits; that is not to say you should never lead them (for example if the opponents avoided NT and that is the only suit not bid, it is probably a safe lead), but there is more risk when you do lead them.  However, they are less dangerous in NT, as often the trick you might lose will come back later in the hand, as declarer cannot trump your low cards.
|FP|2|cp|8|at| 
** |FP||cp||at|The idea behind coded 10s and 9s (which are only used against NT contracts) is to allow partner to distinguish when you do and do not have a tenace. Let us use the coded 10 as an example. If you lead the J, that denies a higher honor, so partner knows you specifically have J10 and nothing higher. Playing coded 10s, you often lead the 10 from AJ10 or KJ10. Let us discuss your having KJ10, although AJ10 is basically the same thing. If partner has the Q, you set up lots of tricks for yourself. If partner has the Ace, you may end up taking all the tricks. If declarer has the Q, then everything works out great, because partner wins the ace and leads back the suit through declarer's Q. If dummy has the Q and it is not played, partner can duck the Ace. If declarer wins the J or K, then partner knows you led from top of nothing; if declarer does not win, partner knows you started with KJ10.
|FP|2|cp|8|at|
** |FP||cp||at|My admonishments about not underleading aces applies to opening leads, which are blind (meaning you can't see dummy and have much less information about declarer's resources). Once several tricks have been played, it can be right to lead away from aces.
|FP|2|cp|8|at|
